 And so there's really said that in the Buddhist teachings, those two, wisdom and compassion,

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:16.000
 or you could say compassion and emptiness, that these are the two fundamental aspects of all of

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:18.000
 Buddhist teaching.

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:23.000
 Wisdom and compassion. And another way to say that is relative truth and absolute truth.

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:26.000
 These are always together. They're always in union.

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:32.000
 And this is a fundamental paradox, too. Really. Because emptiness has two levels of emptiness.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:36.000
 This isn't the second point, but it's separate, separate but involved.

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:42.000
 There's emptiness on the relative truth. We think that the thing is fixed. It's set.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:47.000
 But it actually isn't set. It's totally dependent on all these things to appear the way it is.

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:53.000
 So this is called, it's not fixed. It's interdependent or dependently arisen.

00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:57.000
 But that's just a superficial level, because that's still first-turning teaching.

00:37:57.000 --> 00:38:02.000
 Because we still think there's a thing there. And that's grasping.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:07.000
 Because there's a thing. There's a lotus there. And it has parts and the parts are real.

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:11.000
 But so then it goes, Buddha went, "Oh, so there's actually not a thing there either."

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:17.000
 It's free from all conceptions, from all designations. And this is second-turning teaching.

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:20.000
 Free from any way of designating it.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:25.540
 And that's why this paradox you get to in these middle-weight teachings that Kemper Rinpoche taught

00:38:25.540 --> 00:38:26.000
 this past summer.

